  "The total number of neurons in a neural circuit": "",
  "The total amount of myelin on an axon": "",
  "Summation is the process by which multiple postsynaptic potentials (both excitatory and inhibitory) are added together at the axon hillock to determine whether the net effect reaches threshold and triggers an action potential.": "",
  "A dentist administers a local anesthetic (lidocaine) before drilling a cavity. The patient cannot feel pain in the treated area. Which mechanism explains how the anesthetic prevents pain signal transmission?": "",
  "It opens all K+ channels permanently, hyperpolarizing the neurons": "",
  "It blocks voltage-gated Na+ channels, preventing action potentials from being generated in sensory neurons": "",
  "It destroys the myelin sheath on peripheral nerves": "",
  "It increases GABA release to inhibit all neurons in the area": "",
  "Local anesthetics like lidocaine work by blocking voltage-gated sodium channels on sensory neurons, which prevents the depolarization phase of the action potential and thus blocks pain signal transmission from reaching the brain.": "",
  "A patient taking an SSRI (selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor) for depression asks how the drug works. Which aspect of synaptic transmission does the SSRI specifically target?": "",
  "It blocks the reuptake of serotonin from the synaptic cleft, allowing serotonin to remain active longer": "",
  "It destroys the enzyme that breaks down dopamine": "",
  "It blocks voltage-gated Na+ channels to prevent action potentials": "",
  "It increases the production of serotonin in the neuron cell body": "",
  "SSRIs block the serotonin reuptake transporter on the presynaptic membrane, preventing serotonin from being recycled back into the presynaptic neuron, which increases the concentration and duration of serotonin signaling in the synaptic cleft.": "",
  "A physiology student is conducting a nerve conduction experiment and notices that increasing the stimulus strength beyond threshold does not increase the amplitude of the action potential. Which principle explains this observation?": "",
  "The principle of spatial summation": "",
  "The refractory period principle": "",
  "The principle of temporal summation": "",
  "The all-or-none principle": "",
  "The all-or-none principle dictates that once threshold is reached, the action potential always fires at full amplitude regardless of stimulus strength; the nervous system encodes stimulus intensity through firing frequency rather than action potential size.": "",
